<p>Hey <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/researcherrando" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6982986); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=6982986&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1607912626" alt="ResearcherRando" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=6982986)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/researcherrando" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6982986); return false;">ResearcherRando</a></span>, thanks for bringing these issues up. If we could get some clarification on one of your points, that'd be great.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Snipped&nbsp;for&nbsp;mobile&nbsp;users</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>I think the ability for more freedom in trying to convey what makes an idea worth it could benefit this site greatly. Once again: this spot isn’t impossible, but cam present real problems to someone in trying to cram an idea into a small format.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>What are you suggesting we change, specifically? That we raise the word count limit on idea posts? Authors have a number of resources at their disposal already to receive crit which aren't encumbered by a word limit, whether that's the IRC chatrooms, a couple trusted Discord servers, or other avenues.<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-820888-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-820888-1')">1</a></sup> Moreover the greenlighting process isn't mandatory for posting to the site — it's only a requirement in order to use the draft forum.</p>
<p>With that said, authors seems pretty free to mix and match what styles of critique work for them.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>For a site requiring hard work from new creators, all it takes is ten people deciding to press a button saying they didn’t like it, and that says to the author this page is worthy of deletion.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Bit of a correction here: the -10 deletion threshold means that ten more people downvote the page than upvote it, not that ten people overall downvote.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>in trying to add to something I’ve seen as fun and a little silly, I’ve been met with an incredibly high wall, in some ways earned by the site, but in many ways just as ridiculous.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I agree, it takes a lot of work to get something to stick on this site. If you're driven to see your idea(s) succeed, we encourage you to continue working on them up-until-and-beyond the point that they'll stay on the site. This site's high standards are meant as less of an impassible boundary and more as a motivator.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-820888-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-820888-1')">1</a>. The word limit was initially put in place at the request of critters — before it was implemented, ideas tended to be exceedingly long and directionless. The rule intends to force new authors to streamline their ideas and make them look more appealing to critters (moreso than giant walls of text, anyways). Personally I think 400 words is rather generous.</div>
</div>

